Looking at the code fragments, I can see that `hexi::dynamic_buffer` has `write()` and `read()` methods. Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/dynamic_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
void write_to_dynamic_buffer(hexi::dynamic_buffer<block_size>& buffer, uint32_t header, const std::vector<uint8_t>& data) {
    // Write header (4 bytes)
    buffer.write(reinterpret_cast<const uint8_t*>(&header), sizeof(header));

    // Write data
    if (!data.empty()) {
        buffer.write(data.data(), data.size());
    }
}

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
struct BufferData {
    uint32_t header;
    std::vector<uint8_t> data;
};

BufferData<> read_from_dynamic_buffer(hexi::dynamic_buffer<1024>& buffer, size_t data_length) {
    BufferData<> result;

    // Read header (4 bytes)
    buffer.read(reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(&result.header), sizeof(result.header));

    // Read data of specified length
    if (data_length > 0) {
        result.data.resize(data_length);
        buffer.read(result.data.data(), data_length);
    }

    return result;
}
```

The implementation follows the pattern I observed in the test code fragments where:
- `buffer.write()` is used to write data to the buffer
- `buffer.read()` is used to read data from the buffer
- The header is written/read as a 4-byte `uint32_t` value
- The data is written/read as a byte array of the specified length
- The data vector is resized to the specified length before reading

This matches the usage patterns shown in the test files like `tests/binary_stream_pmc.cpp` and `tests/binary_stream.cpp`.

