Looking at the code fragments from the Hexi library, I can see that it provides endianness conversion functionality through the `hexi::endian` namespace. The key function is `conditional_reverse` which handles the conversion based on the source and target endianness.

Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/endian.h>
#include <cstdint>

template<typename T>
T convert_to_big_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::native, std::endian::big);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_from_big_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::big, std::endian::native);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_to_little_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::native, std::endian::little);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_from_little_endian(T value) {
    return hexi::endian::conditional_reverse(value, std::endian::little, std::endian::native);
}
```

The implementation uses the `hexi::endian::conditional_reverse` function which:
- Takes the value to convert
- The source endianness (what the value is currently in)
- The target endianness (what we want to convert to)

The function automatically handles different data types including:
- Integer types (using `std::byteswap`)
- Float types (by bit-casting to integers, byteswapping, then bit-casting back)
- Double types (same approach as float but with 64-bit integers)

This implementation is clean, type-safe, and leverages the existing functionality provided by the Hexi library.

