Looking at the code fragments, I can see that `hexi::static_buffer` has internal read and write pointers, and we need to preview data without advancing the read pointer. The key insight is that we need to use the buffer's read functionality but then restore the original read position.

Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/static_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

template<size_t buffer_size = 1024>
std::vector<uint8_t> preview_buffer_data(const hexi::static_buffer<std::byte, buffer_size>& buffer, size_t bytes_to_preview) {
    std::vector<uint8_t> result;

    // Get the current read position to restore it later
    auto current_read_pos = buffer.tell();

    // Adjust bytes_to_preview to not exceed available data
    size_t available_bytes = buffer.size();
    if (bytes_to_preview > available_bytes) {
        bytes_to_preview = available_bytes;
    }

    if (bytes_to_preview > 0) {
        // Reserve space in the result vector
        result.resize(bytes_to_preview);

        // Read the data into our vector
        // Note: we need to const_cast because read() is non-const, but we'll restore the position
        const_cast<hexi::static_buffer<std::byte, buffer_size>&>(buffer).read(
            reinterpret_cast<std::byte*>(result.data()), bytes_to_preview);

        // Restore the original read position
        const_cast<hexi::static_buffer<std::byte, buffer_size>&>(buffer).seek(current_read_pos);
    }

    return result;
}
```

However, looking more carefully at the code fragments, I notice that `static_buffer` has `using seeking = supported;` which suggests it supports seeking. But the `seek()` method might not be available in the const version. Let me provide a more robust implementation that handles this properly:

```cpp
#include <hexi/static_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

template<size_t buffer_size = 1024>
std::vector<uint8_t> preview_buffer_data(const hexi::static_buffer<std::byte, buffer_size>& buffer, size_t bytes_to_preview) {
    std::vector<uint8_t> result;

    // Create a non-const reference to work with the buffer's non-const methods
    // This is safe because we're not modifying the buffer's content, just its read position
    auto& non_const_buffer = const_cast<hexi::static_buffer<std::byte, buffer_size>&>(buffer);

    // Get the current read position to restore it later
    auto current_read_pos = non_const_buffer.tell();

    // Adjust bytes_to_preview to not exceed available data
    size_t available_bytes = non_const_buffer.size();
    if (bytes_to_preview > available_bytes) {
        bytes_to_preview = available_bytes;
    }

    if (bytes_to_preview > 0) {
        // Reserve space in the result vector
        result.resize(bytes_to_preview);

        // Read the data into our vector
        non_const_buffer.read(reinterpret_cast<std::byte*>(result.data()), bytes_to_preview);

        // Restore the original read position
        non_const_buffer.seek(current_read_pos);
    }

    return result;
}
```

This implementation:
1. Gets the current read position using `tell()`
2. Reads the requested number of bytes into a vector
3. Restores the original read position using `seek()`
4. Handles edge cases where the requested preview size exceeds available data

The use of `const_cast` is safe here because we're only modifying the read position temporarily and restoring it to its original value, so the observable state of the const buffer remains unchanged.

