Looking at the provided code fragments and the Hexi library structure, I'll implement the varint encoding/decoding functions. Varint encoding encodes integers using a variable number of bytes, where each byte uses 7 bits for data and 1 bit to indicate if more bytes follow.

```cpp
#include <hexi/shared.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

using namespace hexi::detail;

template<typename T>
std::size_t encode_varint(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, T value) {
    static_assert(std::is_integral_v<T> && std::is_unsigned_v<T>, 
                  "encode_varint requires unsigned integral type");

    std::size_t bytes_written = 0;

    do {
        // Take 7 bits of the value
        uint8_t byte = static_cast<uint8_t>(value & 0x7F);
        value >>= 7;

        // Set the continuation bit if there are more bytes to follow
        if (value != 0) {
            byte |= 0x80;
        }

        // Write the byte
        writer.write_byte(byte);
        bytes_written++;

    } while (value != 0);

    return bytes_written;
}

template<typename T>
T decode_varint(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader) {
    static_assert(std::is_integral_v<T> && std::is_unsigned_v<T>, 
                  "decode_varint requires unsigned integral type");

    T result = 0;
    int shift = 0;

    while (true) {
        // Read next byte
        uint8_t byte = reader.read_byte();

        // Add the 7 data bits to the result
        result |= static_cast<T>(byte & 0x7F) << shift;
        shift += 7;

        // Check if this is the last byte (continuation bit not set)
        if ((byte & 0x80) == 0) {
            break;
        }

        // Safety check: prevent shift overflow for the type
        if (shift >= static_cast<int>(sizeof(T) * 8)) {
            // This would overflow the target type
            // In a real implementation, you might want to handle this error
            break;
        }
    }

    return result;
}

template<typename T>
bool encode_decode_roundtrip(T original_value) {
    static_assert(std::is_integral_v<T> && std::is_unsigned_v<T>, 
                  "encode_decode_roundtrip requires unsigned integral type");

    // Create a buffer to hold the encoded data
    std::vector<std::byte> buffer;
    hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor adaptor(buffer);

    // Create writer and encode the value
    hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer writer(adaptor);
    encode_varint<T>(writer, original_value);

    // Check if encoding was successful
    if (writer.state() != hexi::detail::stream_state::ok) {
        return false;
    }

    // Create reader and decode the value
    hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor read_adaptor(buffer);
    hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader reader(read_adaptor);
    T decoded_value = decode_varint<T>(reader);

    // Check if decoding was successful
    if (reader.state() != hexi::detail::stream_state::ok) {
        return false;
    }

    // Compare with original
    return original_value == decoded_value;
}
```

Key implementation details:

1. **encode_varint**: 
   - Processes the value in 7-bit chunks
   - Sets the high bit (0x80) to indicate continuation for all but the last byte
   - Returns the number of bytes written

2. **decode_varint**:
   - Reads bytes until it finds one without the continuation bit set
   - Reconstructs the original value by shifting and ORing the 7-bit chunks
   - Includes safety checks for shift overflow

3. **encode_decode_roundtrip**:
   - Uses `buffer_adaptor` with a `std::vector<std::byte>` as the underlying storage
   - Creates separate writer and reader instances
   - Checks stream state after each operation
   - Compares the original and decoded values

The implementation follows standard varint encoding scheme used in protocols like Protocol Buffers and ensures proper error handling using the Hexi library's stream state mechanism.

