Looking at the code fragments and the Hexi library usage patterns, I can see that `block_allocator` is used for fixed-size object allocation. Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/allocators/block_allocator.h>
#include <vector>
#include <memory>

struct PoolObject {
    int id;
    double value;

    // Default constructor required by block_allocator
    PoolObject() : id(0), value(0.0) {}

    PoolObject(int i, double v) : id(i), value(v) {}
};

std::vector<PoolObject*> create_object_pool(hexi::block_allocator<PoolObject, 10>& allocator) {
    std::vector<PoolObject*> objects;

    // Allocate 3 objects with different values using the block allocator
    PoolObject* obj1 = allocator.allocate();
    if (obj1) {
        *obj1 = PoolObject(1, 10.5);
        objects.push_back(obj1);
    }

    PoolObject* obj2 = allocator.allocate();
    if (obj2) {
        *obj2 = PoolObject(2, 20.7);
        objects.push_back(obj2);
    }

    PoolObject* obj3 = allocator.allocate();
    if (obj3) {
        *obj3 = PoolObject(3, 30.9);
        objects.push_back(obj3);
    }

    return objects;
}
```

The implementation:
1. Creates a vector to store pointers to the allocated objects
2. Uses the `allocate()` method of the `block_allocator` to get memory for each object
3. Checks if allocation was successful (pointer is not null)
4. Assigns values to each allocated object using the parameterized constructor
5. Adds the pointers to the result vector
6. Returns the vector containing the 3 allocated object pointers

The `block_allocator<PoolObject, 10>` template parameter indicates it can hold up to 10 `PoolObject` instances, so allocating 3 objects is well within its capacity.

